Variables
=============

-> Variables are used to store the data
 
       int a = 10;  (int = datatype, a = variable )
	  	   
	   User u1 = new User();
	   
	   Student s1 = new Student ();

-> Vaariables are divided into three types

  a) Global Variables/ instance variables/non-static variables
  b) static variables
  c) Local Variables

====================
instance variables
====================

-> Variables which are declared inside the class and outside the method are called as instance variables

-> instance variables can be accessed by all the methods available in the class that's why it is called as Global variable

-> Initialization is optional for instance variables

-> Instance variables are called as Object variables

-> When we create the object, memory will be allocated for instance variables

   Note:- If we create 2 objects, then memory will be allocated 2 times by JVM for Instance variable.

-> If we don't intialize instance variable, then it will be initialized with default value based on datatype when the object is created

-> Every Object will maintain its own copy of the instance variable.

ex:-

public class User {

    int age;

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        User raju = new User();
        raju.age = 20;
        System.out.println(raju.age);

        User rani = new User();
        rani.age = 25;
        System.out.println(rani.age);
    }
}

output:
20
25


===================================
Static vairable
===================================
-> The variables which are declared inside the class and outside the method with 'static' keyword are called as static variables.

-> Static variables are class level variables

-> When class is loaded into JVM then imidiately memory will be allocated for static variables.

-> Memory will be allocated for static variable only once when the class is loaded into the JVM.

-> All objects of the will maintain the same copy of the static variable.

-> ststic variable can be accessed directly by using class name.

ex:-

public class Students {
	
	String name;
	String email;
	long phno;
	static String institute;
	
	   public static void main(String[] args) {
		   
		   Students.institute = "Ashokit";
		
		   Students Rohit = new Students();
		   Rohit.name ="Rohit";
		   
		   Students Mohit = new Students();
		   Mohit.name ="Mohit";
		   
	     }
	
  }

==================================================
When to declare variables as static or non-static ?
==================================================

-> If we want to store different values based on object then use instance variable.

-> If we want to store same values for all objects then use static variable.


==================
Local variables
==================

-> The variables which are declared inside the method or constructor or block are called as Local Variables.

-> If we declare a variable with in the method, then that variable can be used/accessed only with in that method.

-> Before using local variables,we have to initialize them. 

-> If we create a variable within the method, memory will be allocated for that variable when that method is executing.
   After the method execution completed, local variable will be deleted from the JVM or memory.

ex:- 

class Demo{
      public static void main(String[]args){
	   
	          int a = 10;
			      int b = 20;
			  
			  System.out.println(a);
			  System.out.println(b);
	  
	  }

}
